# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
In this problem , we have find the last node of the linked list and always try to rotate it with joining lastnode to head and previous of last to NULL; 
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The function first checks if the input linked list is empty or if k is zero. If either of these conditions is true, the function returns the input list as it is.

The function then computes the length of the linked list by traversing it using a temporary pointer temp that starts from the head of the list. The length c of the list is incremented for each node encountered.

The function then computes the actual number of positions z by which the list should be rotated. This is done by taking the remainder of k divided by c. This ensures that if k is greater than c, the function rotates the list by only the necessary amount.

The function then enters a loop that rotates the list by z positions. In each iteration, the function traverses the list using a pointer curr that starts from the head of the list and stops at the second-last node. This is because we need to change the next pointer of the second-last node to point to NULL in order to make it the last node of the rotated list. The function then saves the next pointer of the second-last node in a temporary pointer next, sets the next pointer of the second-last node to NULL, and sets the next pointer of next to point to the original head of the list. Finally, the function updates the head of the list to point to next.

The loop runs z times, so the final result is a rotated list.

The function returns a pointer to the new head of the rotated list.
